  11 |            | Differential equations are widely used in science, engineering and economics.  After 400 years there are still lots of open problems to solve.
  12 |            | 
  13 |            | \subsection{Overview}
  14 |            | 
  15 |            | A differential equation is an equation which links $y$,\quad
  16 |            | $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$, \quad $\dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2}$, etc.
  17 |            | 
  18 |            | \begin{examples}\quad
  19 |            | \begin{tabular}{ll}
  20 |            | $\dfrac{dy}{dx}  =  x$ & Easy \\
  21 |            | $\dfrac{dy}{dx}  =  x + y^2$ & Hard \\
  22 |            | $\left(\dfrac{dy}{dx}\right)^2 + \left(\dfrac{dy}{dx}\right)  =  \sin(y)$ & Very hard \\
  23 |            | $\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} + \dfrac{dy}{dx}  =  \sin(x)$ & Easy
  24 |            | \end{tabular}
  25 |            | \end{examples}
  26 |            | 
  27 |            | “Ordinary” means there is only one independent variable.
  28 |            | 
  29 |            | \subsection*{Some terminology}
  30 |            | 
  31 |            | \begin{itemize}
  32 |            | \item The \textbf{order} of a differential equation is the largest
  33 |            | number of derivatives.
  34 |            | 
  35 |            | \begingroup
  36 |            | \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{2}
  37 |            | \begin{tabular}[3]{ll}
  38 |            | $\dfrac{dy}{dx}  =  x$ & \textbf{First} order \\
  39 |            | $\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}  =  x$ & \textbf{Second} order \\
  40 |            | $\dfrac{d^4y}{dx^4} + p \dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} + y  =  0$ &
  41 |            | \textbf{Fourth} order
  42 |            | \end{tabular}
  43 |            | \endgroup
  44 |            | 
  45 |            | \item A differential equation is \textbf{linear} if we only have
  46 |            | $\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2}$, $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ or $y$ and no functions such
  47 |            | as $y^2$.
  48 |            | 
  49 |            | \begin{itemize}
  50 |            | \item Linear equations are easy to solve and very common.
  51 |            | 
  52 |            | \item Nonlinear equations are often \textbf{very} hard to
  53 |            | solve.  The solutions usually use numerical methods.
  54 |            | \end{itemize}
  55 |            | 
  56 |            | \item The \textbf{initial condition(s)} of a differential equation
  57 |            | is information about the solution at a point $x=a$. We need this to find a particular solution to the equation; that is, one that does not depend on any arbitrary constants.
  58 |            | 
  59 |            | \begin{tabular}{ll}
  60 |            |  First order: & Need to know $y(a)$ \\\\
  61 |            |  Second order: & Need to know $y(a)$, $\dfrac{dy(a)}{dx}$
  62 |            | \end{tabular}
  63 |            | \end{itemize}
  64 |            | 
