  67 |            | \subsection{Separable first order differential equations}  \label{sect:sepdiff}
  68 |            | 
  69 |            | \begin{definition}
  70 |            | A \textbf{separable} first order ordinary differential equation has
  71 |            | the form
  72 | [          | \[
  73 | [          | \dfrac{dy}{dx}  =  p(x)q(y).
  74 |            | \]
  75 |            | \end{definition}
  76 |            | 
  77 |            | We can solve these \textbf{directly by integration}:
  78 |            | 
  79 |            | Rearrange and integrate
  80 |            | \begin{align*}
  81 |            | \dfrac{1}{q(y)} \dfrac{dy}{dx}  & =  p(x)  \\
  82 |            | \implies \int \dfrac{1}{q(y)} \dfrac{dy}{dx}dx & = \int p(x)dx  \\
  83 |            | \implies \int \dfrac{dy}{q(y)} & =  \int p(x)dx
  84 |            | % \label{sepde_eqn}
  85 |            | \end{align*}
  86 |            | 
  87 |            | \begin{example}
  88 | [          |  \[
  89 | [          |   \dfrac{dy}{dx} = \dfrac{xe^{x^2}}{y^2}
  90 |            |  \]
  91 |            | 
  92 |            |  Separate and integrate
  93 |            |  \begin{eqnarray*}
  94 |            |   && \int y^2 dy = \int x e^{x^2} dx\\
  95 |            |   &\Rightarrow& \dfrac{y^3}{3} = \dfrac{1}{2} e^{x^2} + c\\
  96 |            |   &\Rightarrow& {y^3} = \dfrac{3}{2} e^{x^2} + c 
  97 |            |  \end{eqnarray*}
  98 |            | 
  99 |            | \end{example}
 100 |            | 
 101 |            | \begin{example}
 102 |            | In the introduction to the course we saw a basic model for world population.  A more sophisticated model for population $p(t)$ might satisfy the differential equation
 103 | [          | \[
 104 | [          | \dfrac{dp}{dt}  = p(M-p).
 105 |            | \]
 106 |            | 
 107 |            | Separating variables and integrating gives
 108 |            | \begin{eqnarray*}
 109 |            | && \int \dfrac{dp}{p(M-p)}  =  \int dt \\
 110 |            | & &\text{LHS use partial fractions} \\
 111 |            | && \dfrac{1}{p(M-p)}  =  \dfrac{\dfrac{1}{M}}{p} +
 112 |            | \dfrac{\dfrac{1}{M}}{M-p} \\
 113 | ||         | &\therefore & \dfrac{1}{M} \ln \left|\dfrac{p}{M-p}\right|
 114 | ||         |  =  t + C.
 115 | ||         | \end{eqnarray*}
 116 | ||         | 
 117 | ||         | To find $C$ we need some initial data. Let $p=p_0$ at $t=0$.
 118 | ||         | \begin{eqnarray*}
 119 | ||||       | &\Rightarrow  & C  =  \dfrac{1}{M} \ln \left|\dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0}\right| \\
 120 | ||||||     | &\therefore & \dfrac{1}{M} \ln \left|\dfrac{p}{M-p}\right|
 121 | ||||||||   |  =  t + \dfrac{1}{M} \ln \left|\dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0}\right|.
 122 | ||||||||   | \end{eqnarray*}
 123 | ||||||||   | 
 124 | ||||||||   | Multiply by $M$ and exponentiate
 125 | ||||||||[  | \[
 126 | ||||||||[  | \frac{p}{M-p}  =  \dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0} e^{Mt}.
 127 | ||||||||   | \]
 128 | ||||||||   | 
 129 | ||||||||   | Rearrange
 130 | ||||||||   | \begin{eqnarray*}
 131 | ||||||||[  | && p  =  \left[ \dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0} e^{Mt}\right] M - \left[
 132 | ||||||||   | \dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0} e^{Mt}\right]p \\
 133 | ||||||||({ | && p\left[1 + \dfrac{p_0}{M-p_0} e^{Mt}\right] = \left( \dfrac{p_0
 134 | ||||||||   | M}{M-p_0}\right) e^{Mt}
 135 | ||||||||   | \end{eqnarray*}
 136 | ||||||||   | \begin{eqnarray*}
 137 | ||||||||   | \therefore \quad  p  &=&  \dfrac{M p_0 e^{Mt}}{M-p_0+p_0 e^{Mt}}\\
 138 | ||||||||   | &=&  \dfrac{M p_0 e^{Mt}}{M-p_0} \cdot  \dfrac{M - p_0}{M-p_0+p_0 e^{Mt}}
 139 | ||||||||   | \end{eqnarray*}
 140 | ||||||||   | % The last expression doesn't seem helpful.
 141 | ||||||||   | 
 142 | ||||||||   | Sketch:
 143 | ||||||||   | 
 144 | ||||||||   | At $t=0$, 
 145 | ||||||||[  | \[
 146 | ||||||||[  | p = \dfrac{M p_0}{M - p_0 + p_0}=p_0.
 147 | ||||||||   | \]
 148 | ||||||||   | 
 149 | ||||||||   | As $t \to \infty$,
 150 | ||||||||[  | \[
 151 | ||||||||[  |  \dfrac{Mp_0}{p_0} = M.
